Linux User Accounts & File Permissions
Create 2 users and secure file access - only one user can read/write.

Create Users
bash
# Create users
sudo useradd person1
sudo useradd person2

# Set passwords
sudo passwd person1    # Enter: person1
sudo passwd person2    # Enter: person2
Create & Secure File
bash
# Create file
touch secure.txt

# Fix ownership (needs sudo!)
sudo chown person1:person1 secure.txt

# Set 600 permissions (owner only)
chmod 600 secure.txt

# Verify
ls -l secure.txt
# Output: -rw------- 1 person1 person1 secure.txt
Test Access
✅ Person1 (Full Access)
bash
su person1
cat secure.txt        # Works
nano secure.txt       # Works (read+write)
exit
❌ Person2 (No Access)
bash
su person2
cat secure.txt        # Permission denied!
exit
Permission Breakdown
Permission	Numeric	Meaning
600	rw-------	Owner r/w only
644	rw-r--r--	Owner r/w, others read
755	rwxr-xr-x	Owner r/w/x, others r/x
Key Commands Summary
bash
sudo useradd user        # Create user
sudo passwd user         # Set password
sudo chown user:user file # Set owner
chmod 600 file           # Owner-only access
ls -l                    # Check permissions
su user                  # Switch user
Common Errors Fixed
text
❌ chown person1:person1 secure.txt
✅ sudo chown person1:person1 secure.txt

❌ chowm 600 secure.txt  
✅ chmod 600 secure.txt
